<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-directional-derivatives">
	<title>Directional derivatives and gradient descent</title>

	<subsection>
		<title>Directional derivatives</title>

		<activity xml:id="act-10-1-solve-equation">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the system of equations satisfied by the critical points of the function
					<me>f(x,y,z) = x^2e^{yz} + y\sin(xz) + z\cos(xy)</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We calculate that
					<me>
						f_x(x,y,z)=2xe^{yz}+yz\cos(xz)-yz\sin(xy)
					</me>,
					that
					<me>
						f_y(x,y,z)=x^2ze^{yz}+\sin(xz)-xz\sin(xy)
					</me>
					and that
					<me>
						f_z(x,y,z)=x^2ye^{yz}+xy\cos(xz)+\cos(xy)
					</me>.
					So the critical points of <m>f</m> are the solutions to the system of equations
					<me>
						\begin{cases}
						2xe^{yz}+yz\cos(xz)-yz\sin(xy)=0,\\
						x^2ze^{yz}+\sin(xz)-xz\sin(xy)=0,\\
						x^2ye^{yz}+xy\cos(xz)+\cos(xy)=0.
						\end{cases}
					</me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<p>
			Using the calculus we have developed, it is usually straightforward to write the equations that critical points must satisfy. <xref ref="act-10-1-solve-equation"/> also shows the problem: those equations may be nonlinear and difficult or impossible to solve exactly. This is different from the linear systems in Unit 2, where Gaussian elimination gave a systematic exact method.
		</p>

		<p>
			For such problems, one often uses numerical methods. Gradient descent starts with an initial guess <m>\mathbf{x}_0</m> and produces iterates
			<me>
				\mathbf{x}_{k+1}=\mathbf{x}_k-\alpha \nabla f(\mathbf{x}_k).
			</me>
			The positive scalar <m>\alpha</m> is the step size. The minus sign moves in a direction where <m>f</m> initially decreases. The method does not automatically converge; the function, starting point, and step size matter.
		</p>

		<p>
			To discuss this further, we must introduce more general kinds of derivatives. Recall that the partial derivatives of a function <m>f</m> are defined as
			<me>
				\frac{\partial f}{\partial x_i}(\mathbf{a}) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(\mathbf{a} + h \mathbf{e}_i) - f(\mathbf{a})}{h}
			</me>.
			By replacing <m>\mathbf{e}_i</m> by a more general unit vector, we obtain the concept of a <em>directional derivative</em>.
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="def-10-1-directional-derivative">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f</m> be a scalar-valued function. Then if <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is a unit vector, the <term>directional derivative</term> of <m>f</m> in the direction of the vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, denoted <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f</m>, is defined as
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{v}} f(\mathbf{a}) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(\mathbf{a} + h \mathbf{v}) - f(\mathbf{a})}{h}
					</me>,
					provided the limit exists.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			The directional derivative represents the rate of change of the function <m>f</m> at the point <m>\mathbf{a}</m> in the direction of the unit vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>. For a function <m>f(x,y)</m> of two variables, the directional derivative <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(\mathbf{a})</m> is the slope of the tangent line to the curve obtained by intersecting the surface <m>z = f(x,y)</m> with the plane containing both the line passing through <m>\mathbf{a}</m> with direction vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, and the <m>z</m> axis.
		</p>

		<remark>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Partial derivatives are a special case of directional derivatives, i.e., we have
					<me>
						\frac{\partial f}{\partial x_i} = D_{\mathbf{e}_i} f
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</remark>

		<p>
			Despite partial derivatives being a special case of directional derivatives, in most circumstances we can compute directional derivatives using partial derivatives, or equivalently, the gradient.
		</p>

		<theorem xml:id="thm-10-1-direction-in-terms-of-gradient">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose <m>f</m> is a function differentiable at a point <m>\mathbf{a}</m>. Then for each unit vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(\mathbf{a}) = \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \cdot \mathbf{v}</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<proof>
				<p>
					We apply the chain rule. We note that <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(\mathbf{a})</m> is equal to the derivative of the function <m>g(t) = f(\mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{v})</m> at <m>t = 0</m> (both derivatives are defined as the same limits). If we write <m>\mathbf{c}(t) = \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{v}</m>, then <m>g = f \circ \mathbf{c}</m>. But the chain rule (<xref ref="sec-9-2-chain-rule-1"/>) implies that
					<me>
						g'(0) = (\nabla f)(\mathbf{c}(0)) \cdot \mathbf{c}'(0) = (\nabla f)(\mathbf{a}) \cdot \mathbf{v}
					</me>.
				</p>
			</proof>
		</theorem>

		<p>
			<xref ref="thm-10-1-direction-in-terms-of-gradient"/> greatly simplifies the computations of directional derivatives.
		</p>

		<activity xml:id="act-u5-dot-product-controls-direction">
			<title>Dot product controls direction</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose
					<me>
						\nabla f(\mathbf{a})=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3\\
						4
						\end{bmatrix}.
					</me>
					Compute <m>D_{\mathbf{v}}f(\mathbf{a})</m> for each unit vector below:
					<me>
						\mathbf{v}_1=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						1\\
						0
						\end{bmatrix},
						\qquad
						\mathbf{v}_2=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						0\\
						1
						\end{bmatrix},
						\qquad
						\mathbf{v}_3=
						\frac15
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3\\
						4
						\end{bmatrix},
						\qquad
						\mathbf{v}_4=
						-\frac15
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3\\
						4
						\end{bmatrix}.
					</me>
				</p>
				<ol marker="a">
					<li><p>Which listed direction gives the largest directional derivative?</p></li>
					<li><p>Which listed direction gives the smallest directional derivative?</p></li>
					<li><p>How is this the Unit 1 dot product appearing again?</p></li>
				</ol>
				<p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U5-LO2, U1-LO1 | C+R | Core]</c></p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Since
					<me>D_{\mathbf{v}}f(\mathbf{a})=\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\cdot\mathbf{v},</me>
					we compute
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{v}_1}f(\mathbf{a})=3,
						\qquad
						D_{\mathbf{v}_2}f(\mathbf{a})=4.
					</me>
					Also,
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{v}_3}f(\mathbf{a})
						=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3\\
						4
						\end{bmatrix}
						\cdot
						\frac15
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3\\
						4
						\end{bmatrix}
						=
						\frac{9+16}{5}=5,
					</me>
					and
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{v}_4}f(\mathbf{a})=-5.
					</me>
					The largest listed directional derivative occurs in direction <m>\mathbf{v}_3</m>, the direction of the gradient. The smallest occurs in direction <m>\mathbf{v}_4</m>, the direction opposite the gradient. This is the Unit 1 dot product measuring alignment: larger positive alignment gives larger directional derivative.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 y + y^2</m>.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute the directional derivative <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(1,2)</m>, where <m>\mathbf{v} = (1/\sqrt{2}, 1/\sqrt{2})</m>, and <m>f(x,y) = x^2y + y^2</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We begin by computing the gradient of <m>f</m> at <m>(1,2)</m>. We have
						<me>
							f_x(x,y) = 2xy \quad\text{and}\quad f_y(x,y) = x^2 + 2y
						</me>.
						So <m>\nabla f(x,y) = (2xy, x^2 + 2y)</m>, and in particular
						<me>\nabla f(1,2) = \begin{bmatrix} 2(1)(2) \\ (1)^2 + 2 (2) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</me>. So
						<me>
							D_{\mathbf{v}} f(1,2) = \nabla f(1,2) \cdot \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 1/\sqrt{2} \end{bmatrix} = 9 / \sqrt{2}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the directional derivative of <m>f</m> at the point <m>(-1,3)</m> in the direction of the vector <m>(-1,\sqrt{3})</m>. That is, compute <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(-1,3)</m>, where <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is the unit vector in the direction of <m>(-1,\sqrt{3})</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						The vector
						<me>
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-1\\
							\sqrt{3}
							\end{bmatrix}
						</me>
						has norm
						<me>
							\sqrt{(-1)^2+(\sqrt{3})^2}=2
						</me>.
						So the unit vector in this direction is
						<me>
							\mathbf{v}
							=
							\frac12
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-1\\
							\sqrt{3}
							\end{bmatrix}
							=
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-1/2\\
							\sqrt{3}/2
							\end{bmatrix}
						</me>.
						For
						<me>
							f(x,y)=x^2y+y^2,
						</me>
						we have
						<me>
							\nabla f(x,y)=
							\begin{bmatrix}
							2xy\\
							x^2+2y
							\end{bmatrix}.
						</me>
						Thus
						<me>
							\nabla f(-1,3)=
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-6\\
							7
							\end{bmatrix}.
						</me>
						Therefore
						<me>
							D_{\mathbf{v}}f(-1,3)
							=
							\nabla f(-1,3)\cdot \mathbf{v}
							=
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-6\\
							7
							\end{bmatrix}
							\cdot
							\begin{bmatrix}
							-1/2\\
							\sqrt{3}/2
							\end{bmatrix}
							=
							3+\frac{7\sqrt{3}}{2}
							=
							\frac{6+7\sqrt{3}}{2}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the gradient of the function <m>f(x,y) = x^3y</m> to find the directional derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>(2,1)</m> in the direction of the unit vector which we placed at <m>(2,1)</m> points in the direction of the point <m>(3,5)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					The unit vector pointing in the direction from <m>(2,1)</m> to <m>(3,5)</m> is the unit vector pointing in the same direction as the vector <m>(3-2,5-1) = (1,4)</m>. This vector has magnitude <m>\sqrt{1^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{17}</m>, so the unit vector pointing in this direction is equal to
					<me>
						\mathbf{v} =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						1/\sqrt{17}\\
						4/\sqrt{17}
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>.
					Now
					<me>
						\nabla f(x,y) =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3x^2 y\\
						x^3
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>,
					and in particular,
					<me>
						\nabla f(2,1) =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						3(2)^2 (1)\\
						(2)^3
						\end{bmatrix}
						=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						12\\
						8
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>.
					So
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{v}} f(2,1) = \nabla f(2,1) \cdot \mathbf{v} =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						12\\
						8
						\end{bmatrix}
						\cdot
						\begin{bmatrix}
						1/\sqrt{17}\\
						4/\sqrt{17}
						\end{bmatrix}
						= \frac{12 + 32}{\sqrt{17}} = \frac{44}{\sqrt{17}}
					</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y)=x^2e^y</m>. Find the directional derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>(2,0)</m> in the direction pointing from <m>(2,0)</m> to <m>(3,0)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The unit vector is <m>(1,0) = \mathbf{e}_1</m>, and
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{e}_1} f(x,y) = f_x(x,y) = 2x e^y
					</me>.
					So in particular
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{e}_1} f(2,0) = 2(2) e^{(0)} = 4
					</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>

		<theorem xml:id="thm-10-1-directional-derivative-extrema">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose that a function <m>f</m> is differentiable at a point <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
					<ul>
						<li>
							If <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) = 0</m>, then <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f(\mathbf{a}) = 0</m> for any unit vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
						</li>
						<li>
							If <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\ne \mathbf{0}</m>, then <m>D_{\mathbf{v}}f(\mathbf{a})</m> is maximized, among unit vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, when
							<me>
								\mathbf{v}=\frac{\nabla f(\mathbf{a})}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|}.
							</me>
							It is minimized when
							<me>
								\mathbf{v}=-\frac{\nabla f(\mathbf{a})}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|}.
							</me>
							The maximum value is <m>\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|</m>, and the minimum value is <m>-\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|</m>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<proof>
				<p>
					We have already verified the theorem when <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) = \mathbf{0}</m> in <xref ref="thm-10-1-direction-in-terms-of-gradient"/>. When <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \neq \mathbf{0}</m>,  <xref ref="thm-10-1-direction-in-terms-of-gradient"/> and the Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality <xref ref="thm-6-1-cauchy-schwarz"/> says that
					<me>
						|D_{\mathbf{u}}(\mathbf{a})| = |\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\cdot \mathbf{u}| \leq \left\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\right\|\|\mathbf{u}\| = \left\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\right\|
					</me>,
					where the inequality is an <em>equality</em> precisely when <m>\mathbf{u}</m> either points in the direction of <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a})</m>, or points in the opposite of this direction. But when <m>\mathbf{u}</m> points in the direction of <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{a})</m>, i.e., when <m>\mathbf{u} = \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) / \| \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|</m>, we have
					<md>
						<mrow>D_{\mathbf{u}} f(\mathbf{a}) \amp = \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \cdot \frac{\nabla f(\mathbf{a})}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|}</mrow>
						<mrow>\amp = \frac{\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \cdot \nabla f(\mathbf{a})}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|} = \frac{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a})\|^2}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|} = \|\nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|</mrow>
					</md>.
					Conversely, one can check that when <m>\mathbf{u} = - \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) / \| \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|</m>, then
					<me>
						D_{\mathbf{u}} f(\mathbf{a}) = - \| \nabla f(\mathbf{a}) \|
					</me>.
					So we see that these two vectors are precisely the maximizer and minimizer of the directional derivatives.
				</p>
			</proof>
		</theorem>

		<figure>
				<caption>The gradient indicates the maximum and minimum values of the directional derivative at a point. Figure 4.41 from Edwin <q>Jed</q> Herman and Gilbert Strang, <em>Calculus Volume 3</em>, OpenStax, © 2018 Rice University, licensed under <url href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/" visual="CC BY-NC-SA 4.0"/>; source: <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/4-6-directional-derivatives-and-the-gradient#CNX_Calc_Figure_14_06_007" visual="OpenStax Figure 4.41"/>.</caption>
			<image source="calc3-fig-4-41.png" width="60%">
				<shortdescription>
					Gradient directions at a point on a surface.
				</shortdescription>
				<description>
					<p>
						A bowl-shaped surface is shown above the <m>xy</m>-plane with a point <m>P_0(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m> on the side of the surface. On the plane below, arrows based at the corresponding point show <m>\nabla f</m> for most rapid increase, <m>-\nabla f</m> for most rapid decrease, and perpendicular directions for zero change in <m>f</m>. Dashed vertical guide lines connect the point on the surface to its location in the domain.
					</p>
				</description>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<activity>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the direction for which the directional derivative of <m>f(x,y) = 3x^2 - 4xy + 2y^2</m> at <m>(-2,3)</m> is a maximum. What is the maximum value of the directional derivative?
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					First, we calculate that
					<me>
						\nabla f(x,y) =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						6x - 4y\\
						-4x + 4y
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>.
					So
					<me>
						\nabla f(-2,3) =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						6(-2) - 4(3)\\
						-4(-2) + 4(3)
						\end{bmatrix}
						=
						\begin{bmatrix}
						-24\\
						20
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>.
					<xref ref="thm-10-1-directional-derivative-extrema"/> tells us that the directional derivative <m>D_{\mathbf{v}} f</m> is maximized when <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is the unit vector pointing in the direction of <m>(-24,20)</m>. Since <m>(-24,20)</m> has magnitude <m>\sqrt{(-24)^2 + (20)^2} = \sqrt{976}</m>, we see the direction which maximizes the directional derivative is
					<me>
						\mathbf{v} =
						\begin{bmatrix}
						-24/\sqrt{976}\\
						20/\sqrt{976}
						\end{bmatrix}
					</me>,
					and the value of the directional derivative in this direction is equal to the magnitude of the gradient, which is <me>\sqrt{976}</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</activity>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Gradient descent</title>

		<remark>
			<statement>
				<p>
					We now return to the gradient descent algorithm, a method for trying to approximate the local minima of a function <m>f</m>. The algorithm works as follows:

					<ol>
						<li>Start at an initial point <m>\mathbf{x}_0</m>.</li>
						<li>Compute the gradient <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{x}_0)</m>.</li>
						<li>Move in the direction of the negative gradient: set <m>\mathbf{x}_1 = \mathbf{x}_0 - \alpha_0 \nabla f(\mathbf{x}_0)</m>, where <m>\alpha_0 > 0</m> is a step size (or learning rate) parameter.</li>
						<li>Repeat steps 2-3 with step sizes <m>\alpha_1, \alpha_2, \dots</m> to successively define points <m>\mathbf{x}_2 = \mathbf{x}_1 - \alpha_1 \nabla f(\mathbf{x}_1)</m>, <m>\mathbf{x}_3 = \mathbf{x}_2 - \alpha_2 \nabla f(\mathbf{x}_2)</m>, and so on, with the hope that these points converge to a local minimum.
					</li>
				</ol>
			</p>

			<p>
				Intuitively, gradient descent works because each successive value <m>\mathbf{x}_k</m> is obtained by shifting the previous value <m>\mathbf{x}_{k-1}</m> in the direction in which the function <m>f</m> decreases the fastest. The algorithm is likely to find local minima of a function <m>f</m>, although a rigorous analysis of this algorithm is quite involved.
			</p>
		</statement>
		</remark>

	<activity xml:id="act-u5-reading-one-gradient-descent-update">
		<title>Reading one gradient descent update</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Assume <c>grad_f(x)</c> computes <m>\nabla f(\mathbf{x})</m>. Consider the line of code
			</p>
			<program language="python"><code><![CDATA[x = x - alpha * grad_f(x)
]]></code></program>
			<ol marker="a">
				<li><p>What mathematical update rule does this line represent?</p></li>
				<li><p>Which quantity is the learning rate?</p></li>
				<li><p>Why must <c>grad_f(x)</c> have the same shape as <c>x</c>?</p></li>
				<li><p>What would change if the minus sign were a plus sign?</p></li>
			</ol>
			<p><em>Tags.</em> <c>[U5-LO3 | C+T | Core]</c></p>
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The line represents the update
				<me>
					\mathbf{x}_{k+1}=\mathbf{x}_k-\alpha\nabla f(\mathbf{x}_k).
				</me>
				The learning rate is <c>alpha</c>. The vector <c>grad_f(x)</c> must have the same shape as <c>x</c>, because the update subtracts one vector from another. If the minus sign were a plus sign, the update would move in the direction of steepest increase rather than steepest decrease.
			</p>
		</solution>
	</activity>

	<activity>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Find an approximate minimum of the function <m>f : \R^2 \to \R</m> defined by
				<me>f(x, y) = x^2 - 3xy + 3y^2 + 5y + 2x</me>
				using gradient descent. Use the starting point <m>\mathbf{x}_0 = (0,0)</m>, a constant step size of <m>0.1</m>, and stop after computing <m>\mathbf{x}_3</m>. You may use a calculator to perform these computations.
			</p>
		</statement>

		<solution>
			<p>
				First, we calculate the gradient:
				<me>
					\nabla f(x, y) = \begin{bmatrix} 2x - 3y + 2 \\ -3x + 6y + 5 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>
				Starting at <m>\mathbf{x}_0 = (0,0)</m>, we successively compute that
				<me>
					\nabla f(0,0) = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>,
				so
				<me>
					\mathbf{x}_1  = \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\end{bmatrix} - 0.1\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -0.2 \\ -0.5 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>.
				We then compute that
				<me>
					\nabla f(-0.2,-0.5) = \begin{bmatrix} -0.4-(-1.5)+2 \\ -3(-0.2)+6(-0.5)+5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3.1 \\ 2.6 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>,
				so
				<me>
					\mathbf{x}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -0.2 \\ -0.5 \end{bmatrix} - 0.1\begin{bmatrix} 3.1 \\ 2.6 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -0.51 \\ -0.76 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>.
				Finally, we compute that
				<me>
					\nabla f(-0.51,-0.76) = \begin{bmatrix} 2(-0.51) - 3(-0.76) + 2 \\ -3(-0.51) + 6(-0.76) + 5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3.26 \\ 1.97 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>,
				so
				<me>
					\mathbf{x}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} -0.51 \\ -0.76 \end{bmatrix} - 0.1\begin{bmatrix} 3.26 \\ 1.97 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -0.836 \\ -0.957 \end{bmatrix}
				</me>.
				We note that for this function, we can precisely compute that <m>f</m> has a critical point at <m>(-9, -16/3)</m>, which by the second derivative test is a local minimum. So <m>\mathbf{x}_3</m> is <em>not</em> a good approximation to the local minimum. But if we continued to iterate this algorithm, we would find that the points <m>\mathbf{x}_k</m> for, say, <m>k \geq 1000</m>, are very close to the true minimum of the function.
			</p>
		</solution>
	</activity>

	<remark>
		<statement>
			<p>
				This algorithm can be rather cumbersome to compute by hand, but if the gradient of a function is easily determined, can be easily done to a large number of iterations on a computer.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</remark>

	<figure>
		<caption>Initial steps of gradient descent for <m>f(x,y)=x^2-3xy+3y^2+5y+2x</m> with starting point <m>\mathbf{a}_0 = (0, 0)</m>. The point <m>\mathbf{a}_n</m> is determined by the rule <m>\mathbf{a}_n = \mathbf{a}_{n-1} - (0.1) \nabla f(\mathbf{a}_{n-1})</m>. Adapted from: Stanford's MATH 51 textbook.</caption>
		<image source="figures/unit5/u5-gradient-descent-quadratic.png" width="80%">
			<shortdescription>
				Surface plot showing the first gradient descent steps from the origin.
			</shortdescription>
			<description>
				<p>
					The figure shows a side view of the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> for <m>f(x,y)=x^2-3xy+3y^2+5y+2x</m> over a small region near the origin. Four red points labeled <m>\mathbf{a}_0</m>, <m>\mathbf{a}_1</m>, <m>\mathbf{a}_2</m>, and <m>\mathbf{a}_3</m> are connected by red line segments on the surface, showing the first three gradient descent steps from <m>(0,0)</m>.
				</p>
			</description>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<activity>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Calculate <m>D_{\mathbf{u}}f(1, -2, 3)</m> in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v} = -\mathbf{i} + 2\mathbf{j} + 2\mathbf{k}</m> for the function
				<me>
					f(x,y,z) = 5x^2 - 2xy + y^2 - 4yz + z^2 + 3xz.
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>

		<solution>
			<p>
				We compute that
				<md>
					<mrow>\|\mathbf{v}\| \amp = \sqrt{(-1)^2 + (2)^2 + (2)^2} = \sqrt{9} = 3</mrow>
				</md>
				So the unit vector in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is the vector
				<md>
					<mrow>\mathbf{u} \amp = \frac{\mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|} = -\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{i} + \frac{2}{3}\mathbf{j} + \frac{2}{3}\mathbf{k}</mrow>
				</md>
				Using the formula for the directional derivative, we find that
				<md>
					<mrow>D_{\mathbf{u}}f(x,y,z) \amp = \nabla f(x,y,z) \cdot \mathbf{u}</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix}10x - 2y\\ -2x + 2y - 4z\\ -4y + 2z + 3x\end{bmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{u}</mrow>
					<mrow>
						\amp = - \frac{10x - 2y}{3} + 2 \frac{-2x + 2y - 4z}{3} + 2 \frac{-4y + 2z + 3x}{3}
					</mrow>
				</md>.
				At the point <m>(1, -2, 3)</m>, we evaluate that
				<me>
					D_{\mathbf{u}}f(1,-2,3) = (23)\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right) + (-18)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right) + (17)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right) = \frac{-25}{3}
				</me>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</activity>

</subsection>
</section>
